1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,804
Humans perceive color through signals produced by cells in the retina called cones.

2
00:00:05,804 --> 00:00:07,514
Light comes into the eye,

3
00:00:07,514 --> 00:00:11,925
hits the cones and the cones set off electrical signals to the brain.

4
00:00:11,925 --> 00:00:14,895
There are typically three types of cones, S,

5
00:00:14,894 --> 00:00:18,324
M and L, for short, medium and long.

6
00:00:18,324 --> 00:00:23,144
They are sensitive to different frequencies or colors of light.

7
00:00:23,144 --> 00:00:25,350
Short cones prefer blue,

8
00:00:25,350 --> 00:00:28,840
medium prefer green and long prefer red.

9
00:00:28,839 --> 00:00:33,030
However around 10% of men and 1% of women,

10
00:00:33,030 --> 00:00:38,185
have mutations that affect these cones and produce what is known as colorblindness.

11
00:00:38,185 --> 00:00:39,495
The most common form,

12
00:00:39,494 --> 00:00:41,549
is a red green colorblindness,

13
00:00:41,549 --> 00:00:46,974
typically caused by the medium cone shifting sensitivity towards red light.

14
00:00:46,975 --> 00:00:50,945
This mutation is something you can read more about in the instructor notes below.

15
00:00:50,945 --> 00:00:52,380
People with this condition,

16
00:00:52,380 --> 00:00:54,780
can't distinguish between red and green,

17
00:00:54,780 --> 00:00:58,765
as shown in this image of a red and a green apple.

18
00:00:58,765 --> 00:01:03,054
There is actually a pretty large fraction of people that are colorblind.

19
00:01:03,054 --> 00:01:06,174
So you should design your visualizations to include them.

20
00:01:06,174 --> 00:01:10,560
Try to stay away from red green palettes and use blue orange instead.

